    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26c.41-42_0001"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">41</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        Arlington, Minnesota
                        November 5, 1958
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Dr. Neihardt,</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>A letter from you carries the glow of Christmas!</p>
                
                <p>You are, indeed, a sensitive, precious friend!</p>
                
                <p>I must thank you immediately for the encouragement you must have known I needed so badly at this time. As yet, I have not had the courage to approach the aristocratic Reader's Digest, but since you suggest it, I shall give it some thought. Any goal worth reaching is certainly worth a try.</p>
                
                <p>In order to acquaint my family with you as much as possible, we have been reading as many of your books a nd poems as are available. The State Library, St. Paul, and the Minneapolis Public Library have been good about supplying material. I was particularly gratified to find a copy of "Black Elk Speaks" in Minneapolis!</p>
                
                <p>You always have the most comfortable aura of contentment and relaxation about you. We are so glad to know that you are happy about your telecourse. Does it require a good deal of work?</p>
                
                <p>The enclosed photo is two years old, and quite informal, but it does look like us.</p>
                
                <p>Thank you again for you heart-lifting letter.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>With affection,</salute>
                
                    <signed>Jessie Erickson</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
            
            
